The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Sunday, February 15, 2004  Nation at a Glance				 																Isro centre theft for panel probe				 																																																	Bangalore (PTI): A high-level committee has been set up to inquire into the theft of titanium alloy rings from Indian Space Research Organisations Liquid Propulsion Systems Centre, Isro chairman G. Madhavan Nair said on Saturday.				 																																																										The theft of 29 rings valued at Rs 22.5 lakh was reported on Thursday from the high security complex of the centre during a routine check.				 																																																										The centre is engaged in the development of liquid and cryogenic propulsion stages for satellite launch vehicles and auxiliary propulsion systems for both launch vehicles and satellites.				 																																																										It is a breach of security, of course.... We have set up a high-level committee to inquire into the theft, Nair told reporters after inaugurating a new tele-medicine facility of Narayana Hrudayalaya on the outskirts of the city.				 																																																										He said the titanium alloy rings, developed at Mishradatu Nigam (Midani) in Hyderabad, were one of the first production lots and had been kept outside for inspection. This is used for experimental packages. It is not a critical item, Nair said.				 																																																										Nair said the Central Industrial Security Force was in charge of the installations security.				 																																																										The centres group director, C.S. Prasad, in a complaint to police said the rings had been brought from the Vikram Sarabhai Space Centre in Thiruvananthapuram.				 																Bollywood Pak concert in March				 																																																	Mumbai (PTI): The Bollywood concert in Pakistan, which was to be held on February 12, has been rescheduled for the first week of March, organisers here said on Saturday.				 																																																										The Bollywood team was ready with visas and suitcases, but the concert had to be postponed due to non-availability of both Akshay Kumar and Shilpa Shetty, said Bunty Walia of G.S. Entertainment.				 																																																										Akshay and Shilpa were to lead around 70 artistes from the film industry to Lahore on February 12 to perform at the show, which will now be held in the first week of March, Walia said. The date has not yet been finalised.				 																																																	sked if they had got Shiv Sena chief Bal Thackerays nod for the trip, Walia said: The concert in Pakistan is a cultural event and a charity show and we have permission from the government of India.				 																																																										Preparations for the show is on, Walia added, and we are only waiting for the green signals from both Akshay and Shilpa.				 																																																										Akshay was not available for comments.				 																Clash at Kalam meeting venue				 																																																	Munger (PTI): The police had to fire 11 rounds in the air on Saturday to quell a mob which was denied entry into the polo ground where President A.P.J. Abdul Kalam was addressing young yoga disciples here. The mob tried to force its way through the eastern entrance of the ground, located in Munger fort.				 																																																										The group pelted stones in which seven persons, including three policemen, were injured. 				 																																																										Kalam also visited the Imarat-e-Shariah which houses the Shariah (court) for Bihar, Jharkhand and Orissa.				 																Pesticide notice				 																																																	Jodhpur (PTI): Taking suo motu cognisance of a newspaper report on the allegedly high content of pesticides in vegetables sold in Jaipur, Rajasthan High Court has issued a notice to the state government. A division bench directed additional advocate-general Narpat Mal Lodha to submit a report by March 9.				 																Explosives seized				 																																																	New Delhi (PTI): Police claim to have averted a possible terror strike in the capital with the arrest of one person and seizure of 4 kg of high-grade explosives from him. A senior police official said Ved Prakash Sharma, resident of Kathua in Jammu and Kashmir, was caught in Mukarba Chowk of north-west Delhi on Friday evening. Sharma was here to hand over the consignment to one Hanif alias Chaudhary, he added.				 																Vigilance cases				 																																																	Bhubaneswar (PTI): Cases were registered against 207 Class I officers during 2003 by the Orissa Vigilance Organisation, the largest number of such officers booked by the state outfit since its creation. An official release said on Saturday that more Class I officers were booked during 2003 than in the previous three years put together. While 54 Class I officers were investigated in 2002, 77 were targeted in 2001 and 49 in 2000, it added.				 																Twin dacoity				 																																																	Howrah: Robbers struck twice in the district and decamped with Rs 39,000 and 570 grams of gold ornaments, leaving three persons severely injured, reports our correspondent. However, the district superintendent of police on Saturday evening denied the robberies had taken place. 																		The Jammu and Kashmir government plans to project Ladakh as a heritage site and destination for Buddhist tourists. Tourism minister Ghulam Hassan Mir said he would promote the region as a Buddhist heritage spot at a global tourism meet in New Delhi.
